Regularization

  • Regularization is a method used to prevent overfitting in a model

    • it adds a penalty term to the loss function that the model is trying to minimize
    • this penalty term discourages the model from learning complex patterns in the training data that do not generalize to new data

  • Regularization is particularly useful when the number of predictors in a model is large

  • Regularization is a form of shrinkage method

    • it works by shrinking the coefficients of the predictors towards zero
    • this has the effect of reducing the variance of the model, at the cost of introducing some bias

  • Here, we discuss two popular regularization methods

    • Lasso regression
    • Ridge regression

\(\newcommand{\E}{\mathbb{E}} \newcommand{\E}{\mathbb{E}} \newcommand{\var}{\mathrm{var}} \newcommand{\cov}{\mathrm{cov}} \newcommand{\Var}{\mathrm{var}} \newcommand{\Cov}{\mathrm{cov}} \newcommand{\Corr}{\mathrm{corr}} \newcommand{\corr}{\mathrm{corr}} \newcommand{\L}{\mathrm{L}} \renewcommand{\P}{\mathrm{P}} \newcommand{\independent}{{\perp\!\!\!\perp}} \newcommand{\indicator}[1]{ \mathbf{1}\{#1\} }\)

  • Why would we want to shrink our coefficients?
  1. Bias-variance tradeoff: The least squares estimates often have lower bias and higher variance, reducing variance could improve prediction
  2. Interpretation: With too many independent variables models become unparsimonious (kitchen sink regressions) and difficult to interpret
  • Sometimes, regularization can help us automatically perform feature selection
  1. Big \(p\) data: OLS models can not handle \(p > n\) data
  2. Multicollinearity: Regularization can help with multicollinearity

Ridge Regression

  • Ridge regression adds a penalty term to the least squares loss function
    • the penalty term is the sum of the squares of the coefficients multiplied by a constant \(\lambda\)
    • \(\lambda\) is a tuning parameter that controls the strength of the penalty
    • the larger the value of \(\lambda\), the greater the penalty on the coefficients

\[ \text{Ridge loss} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 \]

\(\quad\) where \(\lambda \geq 0\) is a hyperparameter controlling how much to shrink coefficients

  • it turns out that the choice of \(\lambda\) is crucial
    • if \(\lambda\) is too small, the model will overfit
    • if \(\lambda\) is too large, the model will underfit

  • \(\hat{\beta}^R = (X'X +\lambda I)^{-1}X'y\)

  • Ridge regression is particularly useful when there is multicollinearity among the predictors

    • multicollinearity can cause the least squares estimates to have high variance
    • Ridge regression can help reduce this variance by shrinking the coefficients

Ridge Regression - An illustration


  • The left panel shows the least squares loss function
    • the pink curve is the loss function for the ridge regression predictions
    • the green curve is the variance
    • the black curve is the squared bias

  • An example using simulated data with n = 50 observations, p = 45 predictors, all nonzero coefficients

  • Horizontal dashed lines indicate the minimum possible MSE

Lasso (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator)

  • Lasso regression adds a penalty term to the least squares loss function
    • the penalty term is the sum of the absolute values of the coefficients multiplied by a constant \(\lambda\)
    • \(\lambda\) is a tuning parameter that controls the strength of the penalty
    • the larger the value of \(\lambda\), the greater the penalty on the coefficients

\[ \text{Lasso loss} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\beta_j| \]

  • the (â1) penalty in LASSO has the effect of forcing some of the coefficient estimates to be exactly equal to zero when the tuning parameter Î» is sufficiently large
    • the LASSO performs variable selection
    • the LASSO yields sparse models â models that involve only a subset of the variables

Lasso Regression - An illustration

LASSO - Advantages and Disadvantages

  • LASSO has the advantage of producing simpler and more interpretable models

    • it can be useful when we have a large number of predictors and we believe that only a subset of them are important
    • it can be used for variable selection

  • LASSO has the disadvantage of being computationally intensive

  • LASSO wonât work well when true models are not sparse

    • many of the variables are important

  • With high collinearity, LASSO arbitrarily selects one feature among the correlated features

  • Coefficient estimates vary quite a bit with slightly different samples

    • predictions will be similar

  • LASSO can select at most n variables

  • We often care about inference rather than prediction; need confidence intervals for \(\hat{Î²}\)

  • Several options:

    1. Post-Lasso (Belloni and Chernozhukov, 2013)
    • After âhard thresholdingâ with LASSO, take the surviving features and run OLS
    • it will give a consistent estimate under some conditions (âapproximate sparsityâ)
    1. Covariance test (Lockhart, Taylor, Tibshirani, 2014)
    • P-value for each variable as it is added to LASSO model
    1. Bayesian LASSO (Park and Casella, 2008)
    • Bayesian model with a Laplacian prior over \(Î²_j\):

. . .

$$ \[\begin{aligned} y_i | \beta, \lambda &\sim N(\beta_0 + x_i^T \beta, \sigma^2) \\ \beta_k | \lambda &\sim Laplace(0, \lambda) \propto exp(-\lambda |\beta_k|) \\ \end{aligned}\]

$$

  • The LASSO estimator corresponds with the mode of the Bayesian posterior

Resampling methods

  • Resampling is a method that involves repeatedly drawing samples from a training set and refitting a model of interest to each sample in order to obtain additional information about the fitted model

  • The two most common resampling methods are

    • bootstrapping
    • cross-validation

  • Main idea

    • These methods refit a model of interest to samples formed from the training set to obtain additional information about the fitted model

  • The bootstrap method involves repeatedly sampling observations from the training set with replacement

    • refitting the model to each ânewâ sample

  • Cross-validation is used to âestimateâ the test error associated with a given model in order to evaluate its performance

  • in statistics, it is used to estimate the sampling distribution of a statistic to form confidence intervals or to test hypotheses

Bootstrapping

  • Fundamental idea: pretend the observed data is the population
  • The general procedures for bootstrapping is as follows
    • Draw a sample of size \(n\) with replacement from the observed data
    • Fit a model to the bootstrap sample
    • Repeat the above two steps \(B\) times to produce \(B\) bootstrap datasets
      • \(B\) is a large number (e.g.Â 1000)
    • Calculate the quantity of interest for each of the \(B\) models (say \(\alpha\), here)
      • they are the bootstrap estimates of \(\alpha\)

  • Applied when there is no theory to compute standard errors, confidence intervals, etc, or the theory cannot be trusted

  • May not always work either, but works quite generally

  • Resample observed data, create multiple samples

  • From each sample, estimate parameters and assess variability

A major use of bootstrapping in Tree-based Models

  • Bagging (bootstrap aggregating) and Random Forests are two popular ensemble learning methods that use bootstrapping

  • Bagging is a method that involves creating multiple copies of the original training data set using the bootstrap method

    • build a separate (classification/regression) tree model on each bootstrap sample
    • combine the results of the models to make a prediction

  • Random Forests

    • a random forest is a slight variation of bagging that builds a large collection of de-correlated trees
      • each tree is built using a different bootstrap sample of the data
      • at each split in the tree, randomly selecting a subset of the predictors at each split
        • this helps to decorrelate the trees
      • the final prediction is made by combining the predictions of the individual trees
  • The random forest algorithm is one of the most powerful machine learning algorithms available today

Cross-Validation - Validation Set Approach first

  • we have hyperparameters to âtuneâ

  • Training set: A subsample used to fit a model (e.g.Â estimate model parameters)

  • Validation set: A subsample used for model selection (e.g.Â hyperparameter tuning)

  • Test set: A subsample used only for (final) model assessment

  • Validation-set approach: randomly divide the training set into two parts

    • a training set and a validation set (holdout set)
    • fit the model on the training set and then assess its performance on the validation set
    • the resulting validation-set error provides an estimate of the test error
      • we can use this estimate to select the best model (e.g.Â the best hyperparameters)

  • This is typically assessed using MSE in the case of a quantitative response

    • misclassification rate in the case of a qualitative (discrete) response

  • Compare performance of linear vs higher-order polynomial terms in a linear regression

  • The validation estimate of the test error can be highly variable

    • depending on precisely which observations are included in the training set and
    • which observations are included in the validation set

  • In the validation approach, only a subset of the observations

    • those that are included in the training set rather than in the validation set â are used to fit the model

  • This suggests that the validation set error may tend to overestimate the test error for the model fit on the entire data set

Cross-Validation â K-fold Cross-Validation

  • K-fold cross-validation is a generalization of the validation set approach
    • the training set is split into \(K\) smaller sets
    • a model is trained using \(K-1\) of the folds as training data
    • the resulting model is validated on the remaining part of the data
    • the process is repeated \(K\) times, with each of the \(K\) folds used exactly once as the validation data
    • the \(K\) results from the folds can then be combined to produce a single estimation of the test error

Cross-Validation - More details

  • The choice of \(K\) in K-fold cross-validation is somewhat arbitrary
    • the most common choice is \(K = 10\)
    • but \(K = 5\) or \(K = 20\) are also popular choices
    • when setting \(K=n\), the method is referred to as leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV)
  • The computational cost can become a concern when \(K\) is large
    • particularly when there are many tuning parameters
    • particularly when the model fitting procedure is computationally expensive
  • Some formal notations (for a quantitative response)
    • Let the \(K\) parts be \(C_1, C_2, . . . C_K\), where \(C_k\) denotes the indices of the observations in part \(k\)
    • There are \(n_k\) observations in part \(k\)
      • if \(N\) is a multiple of \(K\), then \(n_k = n/K\)
    • Compute \(CV_{(K)} = \sum^K_{k=1} \frac{n_k}{n} MSE_k\) where \(MSE_k = \sum_{iâC_k}(y_i â \hat{y}_i)^2/n_k\), and \(\hat{y}_i\) is the fit for observation \(i\), obtained from the data with part \(k\) removed
  • Since each training set is only \((K â 1)/K\) as big as the original training set
    • the estimates of prediction error will typically be biased upward
  • This bias is minimized when \(K = n\) (LOOCV), but this estimate has high variance, as noted earlier
    • \(K = 5 or 10\) provides a good compromise for this bias-variance tradeoff
  • Like our choice of models, our CV decision involves a bias-variance tradeoff

CV for Cost Complexity Pruning

  • In the context of decision trees, cross-validation can be used to select the optimal value of the cost complexity parameter \(\alpha\)
    • this parameter controls the trade-off between the complexity of the tree and its fit to the training data
  • cost-complexity function: \(R_\alpha(T) = R(T) + \alpha|T|\)
    • where \(R(T)\) is the error of the tree \(T\)
    • \(|T|\) is the number of terminal nodes of the tree
    • \(\alpha\) is a non-negative tuning parameter
  • use cross-validation to select the optimal value of \(\alpha\)

Cost Complexity Pruning using Cross-Validation

  • the printcp() function can be used to display the cross-validated error for different values of \(\alpha\)
    • The plotcp() function can be used to plot the cross-validated error as a function of \(\alpha\)
Code 
library(rpart)

# Fit a decision tree
boston.tree<- rpart(medv~., data = train)


# Display the cross-validated error for different values of alpha
printcp(boston.tree)

# test the pruned tree with the optimal value of alpha from cross-validation

cp_min<- boston.tree$cptable[which.min(boston.tree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"]
cv_1se<- boston.tree$cptable[which.min(boston.tree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"xerror"]+ boston.tree$cptable[which.min(boston.tree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"xstd"]

cp_1se<- boston.tree$cptable[which.max(boston.tree$cptable[,"xerror"] <= cv_1se), "CP"]
prune.boston_1se<- prune(boston.tree,
                          cp=cp_1se)


prune.boston_min<- prune(boston.tree,
                          cp=cp_min)
# Compute the test MSE
boston.pred_min<- predict(prune.boston_min, test)
boston.pred_1se<- predict(prune.boston_1se, test)

cat("the mean square test error for min alpha" , mean((boston.pred_min - test$medv)^2), "\n")

Appendix on Boosting

  • Boosting is a general approach to statistical learning that can be applied to many statistical learning methods
    • let us focus on boosting for regression and classification trees
  • As a recap, bagging and random forests involve
    • creating multiple bootstrap samples of the original training data set
    • fitting a separate decision tree to each each of them
    • combining all of the trees in order to create a single predictive model
  • Boosting works in a similar way, except that the trees are grown sequentially
    • each tree is grown using information from previously grown trees
      • boosting does not involve bootstrap sampling
      • each tree is fit on a modified version of the original data set

Appendix on Boosting

its main idea

  • let \(f(x)\) be the true function we are trying to estimate, and \(\hat{f}(x)\) be the current estimate of \(f(x)\)

  • \(y_i\) be the true response, and \(r_i = y_i - \hat{f}(x_i)\) be the residual

  • The following is the boosting algorithm for regression trees:

  1. Set \(\hat{f}(x) = 0\) and \(r_i = y_i\) for all \(i\) in the training set
  2. For \(b = 1, 2, . . . , B\), repeat the following
    • Fit a tree \(\hat{f}_b\) with \(d\) splits (i.e.Â \(d + 1\) terminal nodes) to the training data \((X, r)\)
    • Update \(\hat{f}\) by adding in a shrunken version of the new tree:
      • \(\hat{f}(x_i) â \hat{f}(x_i) + Î»\hat{f}b(x_i)\)
    • Update the residuals, \(r_i â r_i â Î» \hat{f}_b(x_i)\)
  3. Output the boosted model, \(\hat{f}(x_i) = \sum_{b=1}^B Î»\hat{f}_b(x_i)\)

Appendix on Boosting

  • The most popular boosting algorithm now is Gradient Boosting
    • the algorithm is based on the principle of gradient descent
    • it fits a sequence of trees, where each tree is fit to the residuals of the previous tree
    • the predictions of the trees are combined to make a final prediction
  • The xgboost package (âextreme gradient boostingâ) is a popular implementation of the gradient boosting algorithm
    • known for its speed and performance
    • widely used in machine learning competitions

Appendix on Boosting

  • based on the previous model fit, we can find the optimal number of trees
Code 
a<- which.min(model$evaluation_log$test_rmse)

final<- xgboost(data = xgb_train, max_depth = 2, eta = 1,
                  verbose = 0,
                  nrounds = a, 
                  objective = "reg:squarederror")

Appendix on Boosting

  • we can perform cross-validation to select the optimal number of trees
Code 
set.seed(123)
params<- list(eta = 0.01, max_depth = 3, objective = "reg:squarederror")
cv.nround<- 500
cv.nfold<- 10

boston_xgboost_cv<- xgb.cv(data = xgb_train, params = params, nfold = cv.nfold, nrounds = cv.nround, 
                           early_stopping_rounds = 100, verbose = 0, maximize = FALSE, 
                           prediction = TRUE, showsd = TRUE, metrics = "rmse")

boston_xgboost_final<- xgboost(data = xgb_train, params = params,
                               verbose = 0,
                               nrounds = boston_xgboost_cv$best_iteration)

mean((predict(boston_xgboost_final, x_test)- y_test)^2)
[1] 13.80249
